  <static seed="1080" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/LinearInequalities/GraphToSetAndIntervalNotation10.pg">
    <statement><p>For the interval expressed in the number line, write it using set-builder notation and interval notation.</p>
<!-- PTX:WARNING: PGML wanted to center align here. -->
<image xmlns:pi="http://pretextbook.org/2020/pretext/internal" pi:generated="webwork/images/section-quadratic-graphs-and-vertex-form-8-1-12-image-1" width="60%">
<shortdescription>Graph of an interval on a number line. There is a left parenthesis at 0.5 and everything right of that is shaded. To the right of the axis, there is a letter r.</shortdescription>
</image>
<p><fillin characters="30" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><fillin characters="30" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{r \mid r &gt; 0.5\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0.5,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>Since the given graph shades all the values greater than <m>0.5</m> (but not equal to <m>0.5</m>) the graph represents the inequality <m>r &gt; 0.5</m>.</p>
<p>The corresponding set notation is <m>{\{ r \mid r &gt; 0.5 \}}</m>.</p>
<p>The corresponding interval notation is <m>{\left(0.5,\infty \right)}</m>.</p>
</solution>
